post_text: Prentiss County Child Nutrition will now be serving free meals to all Prentiss County School District students beginning Friday, 9/11/2020. Breakfast and Lunch will now be at no cost for students. Under a new USDA ruling, this will continue until funding is depleted or until 12/31/2020. We will also be sending free meals home with students on their scheduled non-attending school days to help families with meal costs. (Saturday and Sunday not included.) If your child still owes a balance for last year or from August 10 through Sept. 10, 2020, please send funds immediately to clear your child's records. All monies that may still remain in a child's account will be carried over until used. We are very excited and thankful to be providing this service to our students.

Work Packet Drop Off: May 13, 2020 or May 14, 2020 or May 16, 2020.

Work packets can be dropped off at school this Wednesday, Thursday, or Saturday from 8:00a.m.-12:00p.m. Please make sure your child’s name is on the outside cover of the work packet or workbook.

Please place the work packets in the appropriate storage container. Containers will be arranged by grade.

Please check with your students home school location on procedures for obtaining personal items or returning textbooks.

Thank you

All questions, concerns, or comments can be emailed to pcsdinfo@prentiss.k12.ms.us

April 1, 2020
Census Day of Action: April 1, 2020
Today is Census Day! You and the families in your districts are encouraged to complete your Census questionnaire. It will only take 10 minutes. You may respond online at www.my2020census.gov, by calling the toll-free number, 1-844-330-2020, or by mailing back the questionnaire you receive in the mail. If you don't have a questionnaire or postcard with a Census ID, you can enter your address online to complete the Census.

Your response matters. Census results help determine how billions of dollars in federal funding flow into states and communities each year. The 2020 Census results will have a direct impact on Mississippi’s federal education funding allocation for years to come.

Monday, March 16, 2020, 4:02 p.m.

Following advice from local healthcare providers the Prentiss County School District will remain closed through March 27, 2020. Our students and employees and their families safety is our top priority. The President’s office has also announced that you should not gather in groups of 10 or more and limit any nonessential travel. The Prentiss County School District will re-evaluate the situation daily. Thank you for your continued support.

Jeff Palmer, Superintendent of Prentiss County School District

Comments, concerns, or questions should be emailed to pcsdinfo@prentiss.k12.ms.us

post_text:
Closing the school district was not an easy decision, and I know this poses a hardship and inconvenience for many families. However, Prentiss County School District hopes this will help slow the spread of COVID-19 and keep our community safe. Keeping students healthy and safe is Prentiss County School District’s number one priority. I encourage all families and teachers to remain informed and take all necessary precautions that have been issued by the CDC. I encourage families and employees to avoid group gatherings, sleep-overs, theatre outings, crowded retail stores, malls, visitors in your home, and non-essential workers in your home. Know that your family’s safety is of the utmost importance and more information will be made available when it is available to us. Thank you for your support.

Jeff Palmer, Superintendent of Prentiss County School District

Comments, concerns, or questions should be emailed to pcsdinfo@prentiss.k12.ms.us

post_text:
PCSD
Teacher of the Week

Name: Mrs. Paris Moreland

School: Wheeler Attendance Center

Subjects Taught: Kindergarten

Years in Education: 5th

Educational Experience: Bachelors of Science Degree in Elementary Education from Blue Mountain College

What is your favorite thing about education? My favorite thing about education is watching my students throughout the year mature and learn. When I see a student that has been struggling and they understand something for the first time or make that very first "100" they've been working so hard for, I think I may get more excited than they do! Teaching kindergarten is a daily challenge, but it is also very rewarding. I'm thankful to be a part of the Wheeler community and part of the Prentiss County School District.

Name: Mr. Andrew Murphy

School: New Site High School

Subjects Taught: Physical Science, Chemistry, Physics, Zoology, and Botany

Years in Education: 7th

Educational Experience: Bachelors of Science Degree from Blue Mountain College

What is your favorite thing about education?: Allowing students to think about the world in a different way by involving them in interesting and fun labs with hands on demonstrations. We recently started the Ecology Club in which we are launching the first Aquaponics Garden at New Site. Students are learning eco-friendly organic farming techniques as well as, nutrient cycles and pollination of plants through hands on experiences.

What is your favorite thing about education?

"One of my favorite things is seeing my former students when I'm out and about or even while at school.
